        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is the cost of a bill of materials calculated?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "BOM cost is the sum of each component quantity multiplied by its rate, plus a scrap allowance, plus conversion cost for the operations involved. A chair using 4 kg steel at Rs 60, Rs 120 of fittings and Rs 90 of labour and overhead costs Rs 450 per unit. Multi-level BOMs roll sub-assembly costs upward into the parent item."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between BOM costing and standard costing?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "BOM costing builds the cost of one finished unit from its component list and routing, while standard costing sets a pre-agreed cost for that unit and measures actual production against it. BOM costing answers what the product should cost today at current rates. Standard costing answers why the factory spent Rs 470 when Rs 450 was expected."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does BOM costing feed the cost records required under Section 148?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "BOM costing supplies the per-unit material and conversion figures that fill the cost records in Form CRA-1, which Section 148 of the Companies Act 2013 requires from specified regulated and non-regulated industries above prescribed turnover limits. Without a maintained BOM the cost sheet cannot reconcile raw material consumed against production quantity, and the cost auditor qualifies the report."
          }
        }
