  <div class="gl-tocbar"><div class="gl-wrap gl-toc"><a href="#definition" class="gl-pill is-active">Definition</a><a href="#what-is" class="gl-pill">What it is</a><a href="#how-works" class="gl-pill">How it works</a><a href="#formula" class="gl-pill">Formula</a><a href="#example" class="gl-pill">Example</a><a href="#mistakes" class="gl-pill">Mistakes</a><a href="#faq-section" class="gl-pill">FAQs</a></div></div>
  <div class="gl-body"><div class="gl-wrap"><div class="gl-grid"><div class="gl-main"><section id="definition" class="gl-sec"><div class="gl-eyebrow">Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing: Definition</div><div class="definition-box"><p>Bill of Materials (BOM) costing is the method of building up a finished product&#x27;s cost from the list of every raw material, component and sub-assembly that goes into it, priced and totalled. It lives in the inventory or manufacturing module of the accounting system. It matters because it gives an accurate per-unit cost for pricing, valuing stock and measuring whether production is running to plan.</p></div></section><section id="what-is" class="gl-sec"><h2>What Is Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing?</h2><p>A bill of materials is the recipe for a product — the exact quantity of each input needed to make one unit. BOM costing puts a price against every line of that recipe and adds any direct labour and absorbed overhead, so the business knows what a finished unit truly costs to make. Change a component price or a quantity, and the product cost updates through the BOM.</p><p>An Indian manufacturer meets BOM costing whenever it prices a product, values closing stock, or reconciles material consumption. It underpins the cost records prescribed in Form CRA-1 under the Companies (Cost Records and Audit) Rules 2014, which specifically expect a bill of material to be maintained for each product. It also drives the material cost that feeds inventory valuation under AS 2 or Ind AS 2.</p><div class="key-terms"><p class="key-terms__title">Key terms</p><ul><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/fifo-vs-weighted-average-cost">FIFO vs Weighted Average Cost</a> — The formula that prices the materials in the BOM.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/standard-cost-variance">Standard Cost Variance</a> — Comparing BOM standard cost to actual to find variances.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/inter-company-ledger-reconciliation">Inter-Company Ledger Reconciliation</a> — Reconciling component transfers between group entities.</li></ul></div></section><section id="why-matters" class="gl-sec"><h2>Why Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing Matters</h2><p>A wrong BOM cost quietly poisons pricing, stock value and margins:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Mispriced products</strong> — An understated BOM cost leads to prices that do not cover cost, so the business loses money on every unit sold.</li><li><strong>Wrong inventory valuation</strong> — Finished goods valued on a faulty BOM misstate closing stock and, through it, reported profit.</li><li><strong>Undetected material leakage</strong> — Without a BOM to compare against, excess consumption or wastage in production goes unnoticed.</li><li><strong>Cost-record and audit issues</strong> — Companies under cost audit must maintain accurate BOM-based records; gaps draw a cost-audit qualification.</li><li><strong>Poor make-or-buy calls</strong> — Deciding whether to make or outsource a component needs a reliable BOM cost; a wrong one misguides the decision.</li></ul></section><section id="how-works" class="gl-sec"><h2>How Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing Works - Step by Step</h2><p>A product cost is assembled from its BOM in a defined sequence:</p><ol class="step-cards"><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">1</span><strong>Build the bill of materials</strong><p>Engineering lists each input and quantity per unit — the BOM master that everything else prices.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">2</span><strong>Price each material line</strong><p>The accountant applies the inventory cost (FIFO or weighted average) to each component quantity.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">3</span><strong>Add direct labour</strong><p>Labour time per unit is costed at the wage rate and added to material cost.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">4</span><strong>Absorb overhead</strong><p>A share of cost-centre overhead is absorbed on machine or labour hours to reach full cost.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">5</span><strong>Value output and compare</strong><p>The finished-unit cost values production and closing stock, and is compared against actuals to flag variances.</p></li></ol></section><section id="formula" class="gl-sec"><h2>How to Calculate Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing</h2><div class="formula-box"><code>BOM cost per unit = Σ (component quantity × component rate) + direct labour + absorbed overhead</code></div><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Input</th><th>Where it comes from</th><th>Sample value (INR)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Materials (from BOM × rates)</td><td>BOM master × inventory cost</td><td>640</td></tr><tr><td>Direct labour</td><td>Time per unit × wage rate</td><td>120</td></tr><tr><td>Absorbed overhead</td><td>Overhead rate × machine hours</td><td>90</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="worked-result">BOM cost per unit = 640 + 120 + 90 = ₹850. Producing 2,000 units gives a total production cost of ₹17,00,000 to value against actual spend.</p></section><section id="example" class="gl-sec"><h2>Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing: A Practical Example</h2><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Particulars</th><th>Amount (INR)</th><th>Treatment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Steel body - 2 kg @ ₹220</td><td>440</td><td>Material line in BOM</td></tr><tr><td>Motor assembly - 1 unit</td><td>200</td><td>Material line in BOM</td></tr><tr><td>Direct labour - 0.5 hr @ ₹240</td><td>120</td><td>Direct conversion cost</td></tr><tr><td>Absorbed overhead</td><td>90</td><td>Charged on machine hours</td></tr><tr><td>Total cost per finished unit</td><td>850</td><td>Values output and closing stock</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A Pune appliances manufacturer builds up the cost of a small pump from its BOM: ₹440 of steel, ₹200 for the motor, ₹120 of direct labour and ₹90 of overhead — ₹850 a unit. When the steel rate rises to ₹240 a kg, the BOM instantly reprices the pump to ₹890, prompting a review of the selling price before margins are eroded quietly.</p></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--error"><span class="gl-callout__ic">!</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Common error</div><p>Outdated component rates: Costing on last year's material prices understates cost and overstates margin → refresh rates from current inventory cost.</p></div></div><section id="mistakes" class="gl-sec"><h2>Common Mistakes With Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing</h2><p>BOM costs drift wrong when the recipe or the rates go stale:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Outdated component rates</strong> — Costing on last year&#x27;s material prices understates cost and overstates margin → refresh rates from current inventory cost.</li><li><strong>Wrong quantities in the BOM</strong> — A BOM that does not match actual usage misstates cost and hides wastage → reconcile BOM quantities to real consumption.</li><li><strong>Ignoring overhead</strong> — Costing only materials and labour omits overhead, so &#x27;cost&#x27; is below true cost → absorb overhead on a consistent basis.</li><li><strong>Not updating after a design change</strong> — Changing a component without updating the BOM leaves the cost wrong → tie BOM revisions to engineering change notes.</li></ul></section><section id="related" class="gl-sec"><h2>Related Accounting Terms</h2><p>Costing terms that feed and use the BOM:</p><ul class="related-terms"><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/fifo-vs-weighted-average-cost">FIFO vs Weighted Average Cost</a> — The formula that prices the materials in the BOM.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/standard-cost-variance">Standard Cost Variance</a> — Comparing BOM standard to actual to find variances.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/inter-company-ledger-reconciliation">Inter-Company Ledger Reconciliation</a> — Reconciling component transfers between group entities.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting Terms Glossary</a> — Browse every accounting term in one place.</li></ul></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--summary"><span class="gl-callout__ic">&#10003;</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Quick summary</div><p>Bill of Materials (BOM) costing is the method of building up a finished product&amp;#x27;s cost from the list of every raw material, component and sub-assembly that goes into it, priced and totalled. It lives in the inventory or manufacturing module of the accounting system. It matters because it gives an accurate per-unit cost for pricing, valuing stock and measuring whether production is running to plan.</p></div></div><section class="gl-cta"><div class="gl-cta__t"><h3>Need help with Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing?</h3><p>Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing sits inside your day-to-day books. Patron's CA-led team keeps them accurate, compliant and audit-ready.</p></div><div class="gl-cta__btns"><a class="gl-cta__primary" href="/inventory-accounting-costing-services">Inventory Accounting &amp; Costing &rarr;</a><a class="gl-cta__phone" href="tel:+919459456700">Book a consultation: +91 94594 56700</a></div></section></div><aside class="gl-aside"><div class="gl-card gl-card--service"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related service</div><div class="gl-card__name">Inventory Accounting &amp; Costing</div><p>CA-led bookkeeping, compliance and reporting for Indian businesses.</p><a class="gl-card__cta" href="/inventory-accounting-costing-services">Explore the service &rarr;</a></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related services</div><ul><li><a href="/accounting-services-for-manufacturing">Manufacturing Accounting Services<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related terms</div><ul><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/fifo-vs-weighted-average-cost">FIFO vs Weighted Average Cost<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/standard-cost-variance">Standard Cost Variance<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/inter-company-ledger-reconciliation">Inter-Company Ledger Reconciliation<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting Terms Glossary<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div></aside></div></div></div>
  <section id="faq-section" class="gl-faq-section"><div class="faq-expanded"><aside class="faq-expanded__aside"><h2 class="faq-expanded__title">Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing FAQs</h2><p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing for Indian businesses.</p><a class="faq-expanded__cta" href="/contact-us">Still have a question? Talk to a CA &rarr;</a><form class="faq-enquiry" action="https://www.patronaccounting.com/enquiry" method="post" novalidate><h3 class="faq-enquiry__title">Talk to a CA about your books</h3><p class="faq-enquiry__sub">Share your accounting software and we'll scope the work.</p><p class="faq-enquiry__context">Enquiring about: <strong>Bill of Materials (BOM) Costing</strong></p><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="text" name="name" placeholder="Your name" required><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="email" name="email" placeholder="Email" required><div class="faq-enquiry__phone"><span class="faq-enquiry__cc">+91</span><input class="faq-enquiry__input faq-enquiry__input--phone" type="tel" name="phone" placeholder="Mobile" required></div><button class="faq-enquiry__btn" type="submit">Get a Callback</button><p class="faq-enquiry__msg" role="status" aria-live="polite"></p><div class="faq-enquiry__badges"><span class="faq-enquiry__badge"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg>CA-led team</span></div></form></aside><div class="faq-expanded__list"><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a1">How is the cost of a bill of materials calculated?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a1"><p>BOM cost is the sum of each component quantity multiplied by its rate, plus a scrap allowance, plus conversion cost for the operations involved. A chair using 4 kg steel at Rs 60, Rs 120 of fittings and Rs 90 of labour and overhead costs Rs 450 per unit. Multi-level BOMs roll sub-assembly costs upward into the parent item.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a2">What is the difference between BOM costing and standard costing?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a2"><p>BOM costing builds the cost of one finished unit from its component list and routing, while standard costing sets a pre-agreed cost for that unit and measures actual production against it. BOM costing answers what the product should cost today at current rates. Standard costing answers why the factory spent Rs 470 when Rs 450 was expected.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a3">How does BOM costing feed the cost records required under Section 148?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a3"><p>BOM costing supplies the per-unit material and conversion figures that fill the cost records in Form CRA-1, which Section 148 of the Companies Act 2013 requires from specified regulated and non-regulated industries above prescribed turnover limits. Without a maintained BOM the cost sheet cannot reconcile raw material consumed against production quantity, and the cost auditor qualifies the report.</p></div></div></div></div></section>
